The number of Covid-19 patients admitted in various hospitals has continued to decline compared to the start of the month. For instance, 960 patients were admitted in various health facilities across the country on Monday compared to 1,275 on December 1. Similarly, the number of patients under the home-based care as of Monday were 6,581 compared to 8,070 on December 2. “Forty-nine patients are in the intensive care unit, 27 of whom are on ventilator support and 20 on supplemental oxygen. Two are under observation,” Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement on Monday. “Another 46 patients are separately on supplemental oxygen out of whom 37 are in the general wards and nine in the high dependency unit,” Kagwe said. On December 1, there were 71 patients in the ICU and another 88 on supplemental oxygen with 70 of them in the general wards. The death toll from the virus has continued to rise, with Kagwe confirming that six more patients had succumbed to the virus on Monday. The number of lives lost due to the disease now stands at 1,593. The CS said 163 more people tested positive for the virus, raising the country’s caseload to 92,055. The new cases were from a sample size of 2,283 tested in 24 hours, representing a positivity rate of 7.13 per cent. All the new cases were Kenyans except seven who were foreigners, comprising of 84 men and 79 women aged between one year and 88 years. “Today, 424 patients have recovered from the disease, 378 from the home-based care programme while 46 have been discharged from various hospitals. Total recoveries now stand at 73,452.” Nairobi continued to lead after registering 94 new cases distributed across Lang’ata with 11, Starehe and Westlands with 10 cases each, Kibra nine, Ruaraka eight, Embakasi Central seven, Embakasi East and Makadara six cases each, Embakasi West and Kasarani five cases, Roysambu four, Dagoretti North, Kamukunji and Mathare three cases each, Embakasi two while Dagoretti South and Embakasi South had one case each. Kiambu recorded 15 cases, while Homa Bay recorded eight cases, Uasin Gishu seven, Nakuru six, Machakos five, Murang’a , Kisumu and Trans Nzoia three cases each. Mombasa, Kajiado, Meru, Laikipia and Kakamega had two cases each, while Isiolo, Makueni, Bungoma, Migori, Nyandarua, Tharaka Nithi, Kirinyaga, Embu, Narok and Vihiga had one case each.